1 WHEREAS, among the early patriots who supported the cause of American liberty
2 and independence was Haym Salomon, a Jewish patriot and financier who played a critical
3 role in supporting the Continental Congress and aiding the Revolutionary War effort through
4 financial services and personal sacrifice, helping to sustain the cause of liberty during the
5 nation's founding struggle for freedom; and
6 WHEREAS, President George Washington, in his historic 1790 letter to the Hebrew
7 Congregation in Newport, Rhode Island, articulated one of the enduring principles of
8 American religious liberty, declaring that the United States "gives to bigotry no sanction, to
9 persecution no assistance," a statement that continues to reflect the nation's commitment to
10 religious freedom and equal protection under the law for all people; and
11 WHEREAS, the state of Louisiana is enriched by Jewish citizens and institutions that
12 have contributed to the arts, business, medicine, law, education, charitable endeavors, public
13 leadership, and the preservation of religious liberty throughout the state's history; and
14 WHEREAS, Christians acknowledge with gratitude the enduring witness and
15 heritage of the Jewish people, through whom the Scriptures were preserved and through
16 whose long historical experience and testimony the broader principles of faith, religious
17 identity, and religious liberty have been strengthened and advanced; and
18 WHEREAS, Israel and in particular Jerusalem, Judea, and Samaria are historically
19 and Biblically significant regions of Israel that hold profound religious and cultural
20 importance in the shared heritage of Judaism and Christianity and are among the principal
21 places where the Holy Bible records many events of the Hebrew prophets and the life and
22 ministry of Jesus Christ; and
23 WHEREAS, the enduring influence of Israel, and especially Jerusalem, Judea, and
24 Samaria, is reflected throughout Louisiana and the United States in the names of
25 communities, churches, religious institutions, and places inspired by the history, geography,
26 and traditions of the Holy Land and our shared Judeo-Christian heritage; and
27 WHEREAS, May is nationally recognized as Jewish-American Heritage Month, first
28 proclaimed in 2006 and observed annually to celebrate the accomplishments and heritage
29 of Jewish Americans; and
30 WHEREAS, in further recognition of Jewish-American Heritage Month and in
